TikTok hides unwanted videos from users
According to TikTok, the number of its users in the world exceeds 500 million, 40% of which are under 18 years old.
Imagine China / Reuters
Chinese social network TikTok censors videos that mention Tiananmen Square, Tibetan independence or the banned religious group Falun Gong, The Guardian reports.
Documents obtained by the publication say that the owner of TikTok (ByteDance company) with the help of the application promotes the goals of China's foreign policy abroad.
Most of the violations related to China’s policy fall under the “incitement of hatred”.
In each case, TikTok places objectionable posts in a context suited to the general rules so that the actions of the social network do not look like censorship.
For example, the ban on criticism of China’s socialist system falls under the general ban on “criticism or attacks on the policies and social rules of any country, such as a constitutional monarchy, a parliamentary system, etc.”
The ban on mentioning incidents in Tiananmen Square or genocide in Cambodia falls under the "distortion of the history of China or other countries."
The document also lists the banned names of twenty "foreign leaders or statesmen", including North Korean leaders Kim Jong Il, Kim Il-sung and Kim Jong-un, Indian politician Mahatma Gandhi, US presidents Donald Trump and Barack Obama, Japanese Prime Minister Shinzo Abe, South Korean President Park Geun-hee, Indonesian President Joko Widodo and Indian Prime Minister Narendra Modi.
Prohibited material is divided into two categories, the document says.
Publications from the first category are removed by the administrators of the social network and can lead to the blocking of the user.
Not too strict violations belong to the second category: such publications remain on the site, but their distribution is limited to TikTok algorithms.
ByteDance representatives told The Guardian that these rules are outdated and no longer apply: “We are now using a localized approach for moderation, as well as attracting independent local specialists.”
Russian users TikTok has no specific restrictions on publications, says co-founder of the "Production Center" Rustem Bogdanov.
"Production Center" is one of the Russian media companies that officially cooperates with TikTok.
All advertising materials of bloggers "Production Center" agrees with representatives of the social network, but user materials can be placed without agreement, Bogdanov reports.
When asked whether TikTok can speak about politics or Putin, Bogdanov answers in the affirmative and says that he has seen similar publications.
Roman Zaripov, founder of Our Digital, agrees with Bogdanov: “The basic rules for TikTok users are listed in the user agreement: you can not post shocking content, discriminatory statements, and so on.”
But under these rules, you can bring any content that moderators do not like, Zaripov notes.
Zaripova Agency is another Russian partner of TikTok.
According to TikTok, the number of its users in the world exceeds 500 million, 40% of which are under the age of 18.
Under the user agreement, TikTok can only be used by persons over the age of 13.
The administrators of the social network check their age with the help of artificial intelligence: the neural network analyzes faces and determines how old a person looks, Bogdanov says.
If the neural network decides that the user is younger, its account can be deleted, he adds.
According to RBC, in September 2019, ByteDance opened an office in Moscow on the territory of WeWork coworking.
